column168: A shipment of lab chemicals and supplies from Fisher Scientific Co. was delivered by THE CONNECTION CO. and recieved Aug.2, 2006. The shipment contained 7 pieces including 3 boxes of dichloromethane, each box containing four 4 liter bottles. On August 3 at @ 11 am, while breaking apart the shipment for internal on-site delivery. Warehouse personnel dicovered that one of the boxes was stained. Upon opening the box,it was discovered that one of the bottles had been brokened. No dichloromethane remained in it. On August 4, lab personnel whom had ordered the dichloromethane discovered that a another bottle was only @ half full. This indicates that the cap was loose and at some point the box may have been laying on its side. The dichloromethane had partially dissolved the polystyrene inner packaging and stained the box.

1 jug was found empty upon arrival at consignee.  Cap was missing and unsure if was loaded that way from shipper or when the actual release occurred.  No residue was found in trailer.  May have been loaded that way from shipper.
column169: Double check product loaded at shipper before leaving shipper to assure product is safe for travel and all product is accounted for and all caps / lids are secure.

column168: In accordance with 49 CFR 173.241 (b), the product was shipped in a non-DOT specification cargo tank motor vehicle suitable for transport of liquids.  The tank truck has a four bolt flange assembly that connects to a quick disconnect hose coupler.  One of the bolts on the flange failed, allowing product to flow from the tank truck.  The vehicle was located in a gravel parking lot near the intersection of interstate 264 East and 64 East.  Absorbant material was placed near the location of the leak and the remaining product within the tank truck was pumped to IBC's.  In addition, a catch pan was placed under the truck to contain leaking product while remainder of product was being transferred.  The leak was contained to the gravel parking lot and did not enter any waterway or storm sewer.  Absorbant material was collected, along with impacted gravel from the parking lot for proper disposal.  A total of 3 drums containing absorbant material and gravel was removed from the site.
column169: Ulrich pesonnel will increase the frequency of the four bolt flange inspection to prevent future recurrences.

column168: DRIVER HAD BEEN TRAVELLING THROUGH A HEAVY RAINSTORM.  GAS(VAPOR) WAS VENTING(NORMAL) ON HIS ARGON TRAILER.  SAFETY VALVE WAS WORKING AS IT WAS DESIGNED.  WHEN SAFETY VALVE COULD NOT MAINTAIN PRESSURE UNDER 38PSIG, A BURSTING DISC BLEW (AS IT IS DESIGNED TO DO) AND THE PRESSURE IN THE TRAILER WAS RELEASED.  THIS EVENT OCCURED AT 1130.  AT NOON THE PRESSURE IN THE TRAILER WAS ZERO PSIG(O).  AN AIR LIQUIDE SERVICE TECH FROM GRAND RAPIDS, OHIO TRAVELLED TO THE SITE AND REPLACED THE BLOWN DISC.  UNIT WAS INSPECTED BY MICHIGAN STATE POLICE.  NO DEFECT WERE FOUND.  UNIT RETURNED TO HAMILTON, ON, CA FOR INSPECTION.  AIR LIQUIDE MANAGER/EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR ADVISED STATE POLICE NOT TO SHUT DOWN 1 LANE OF HIGHWAY AS PRODUCT WAS NOT A HAZARD TO THE PUBLIC.  OFFICER REFUSED TO DO SO, KEPT ONE LANE CLOSED UNITL SERVICE TECH ARRRIVED ON SCENE.  (6HRS LATER). REPAIR TOOK 18 MINUTES.
column169: ALL SAFETY DEVICES WERE WORKING AS THEY WERE DESIGNED TO DO.  WE SPECULATE THAT THE HEAVY RAIN MAY HAVE CAUSED THE 1ST SAFETY VALVE TO FREEZE SHUT (-300F).  PRESSURE THEN BUILT UP AND CAUSED THE 2ND SAFETY DEVICE (BURSTING DISC) TO BLOW.  AFTER INSPECTION OF TRAILER, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ALL DEVICES WERE OPERATIONAL.    ATTACHMENTS:    1)DATA FROM U 1A FROM MANUFACTURER OF TRAILER  2)MICHIGAN STATE POLICE REPORT  3)HAZMAT CERTIFICATE OF REGISTRATION - AIR LIQUIDE  4)HAZMAT CERTIFICATE OF REGISTRATION - HARMAC TRANSPORT  5)SITE DIAGRAM

column168: At 11:30 the loaders began loading railcar ACFX 86869 and finished loading ACFX 75329 with HSDSL.  The loading arm and spout was left attached to railcar ACFX 75329 so that the arm could drain completely while the loaders tended to other railcars.  At 11:50 the tankfield Unit Operator (head operator) called the loaders on the radio and notified them that they had lost suction on the High Sulfur Diesel tank and a new tank was being set to them.  Immediately after the radio call the loaders witnessed a large air bubble and splash of product coming from the dome of railcar ACFX 75329.  They quickly checked the railcar, noticed it was overfilled and verified that the loading valve was blocked.  The valve was leaking and continued to fill the railcar slowly from the time it was originally blocked in.  The loaders notified the Lead Carloader and their Supervisor who then requested a vacuum truck and instructed the loaders to place some 5 gallon cans under the railcar to catch any spillage.  Tankfield operators were notified and an additional valve upstream of the loading rack was blocked in to help stop the flow of product.  HSDSL continued to escape from the dome as the railcar heated up in the sun (product expansion) and the loading arm valve continued to leak.  Approximately 3 gallons of HSDSL was spilled onto the bare soil.  The vacuum truck arrived on the scene at 12:10 and promptly removed the excess product from the railcar, the 5 gallon cans, and the spill on the ground.
column169: A new valve has been ordered to replace the leaking one.  This incident will be communicated to the railcar loaders during their next safety meeting.

According to the information obtained the following occurred.  During a DOT inspection at a weigh station off of Interstate 25 exit 11 a release was discovered coming from the trailer. The Trinidad Fire Department responded to assess the site.  The ramp to the weigh station was shut down for safety reasons.  RMCAT Environmental Services, Inc. of Colorado Springs, CO was dispatched to investigate the trailer and perform the cleanup.  RMCAT Environmental Services, Inc. investigated the trailer and discovered one damaged 5-gallon plastic pail.  Approximately 2 cups of free product were released and impacted some adjacent freight.  RMCAT Environmental Services, Inc. performed the cleanup using absorbent material.  The cleanup materials, impacted freight and damaged pail were placed into 4,30-gallon drum for disposal.  RMCAT Environmental Services, Inc. will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the cleanup.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Werner Enterprises will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

Driver arrived at consignee and was directed to one of two storage tanks.  Driver was instructed by consignee personnel to delivery product into the specified storage tank.  Aproximately 50 percent of product transferred when storage tank began to overflow approximately 200 gallons into secondary containment.  Driver shutdown transfer process and secured equipment.  Consignee notified fire department.  Consignee personnel responded to clean up.  Driver then instructed by consignee personnel to deliver balance into the other storage tank.

column168: Truck traveling east on Hwy 4 to Hwy 242 south lost control on the exit ramp and went over the embankment. As the trailer jackknifed it tore the truck tank from the railing and ripped a hole in the back side of the truck tank causing a major leak. Because the tank was not stable two tow trucks had to be called to stablize tank before the tanks could be pumped out. Approximately 3,000 gallons leaked onto the ground over 7 hours. Some went into a storm drain and was captured at the end of the drain by a hazardous materials cleanup truck. The balance of the spill went into the soil and is being removed and replaced with clean soil.

column168: BNSF mechanical personnel reported TILX 200335 was leaking product from the manway area during switching movement in the railyard. TILX 200335 was carefully isolated in the railyard with a receptacle placed under this tank car to catch any drippage off the shell. BNSF mechanical responders ensured that all the manway securement bolts were tool tight and suspected that the manway gasket was not sealing properly. A BNSF/shipper contract responder inspected TILX 200335 and reported finding the manway nozzle/manway cover gasket was grooved. Responder replaced the Teflon gasket in kind and resecured the manway closure by 1555 hrs. CDT, 8/04/06. Responder reported that all spillage had evaporated. Afterwards, TILX 200335 was moved in the railyard and no further leakage was observed. TILX 200335 was released to proceed to its destination.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER'S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT RELATES TO THE TOTAL SECUREMENT AND MECHANICAL FITNESS OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: A local resident reported to CHEMTREC that GATX 93666 was venting intermittently. GATX 93666 was standing in a yard/industry track awaiting placement into the consignee’s facility for unloading. This location was adjacent to the property owner whom notified CHEMTREC of this venting event. GATX 93666 was venting from the functioning pressure relief device (PRD). Ambient daytime temperatures had been above 100 degrees F for several days. BNSF contacted the consignee and requested that some product inside GATX 93666 be reduced to allow for additional product expansion from high daytime temperatures until GATX 93666 could be fully unloaded. Consignee transferred approximately 10,000 gallons of product from GATX 93666 into tanker trucks by 0100 hrs. MDT, 8/03/06 without further incident. No further venting was reported from GATX 93666 afterwards. GATX 93666 was placed into consignee’s facility for further unloading on 8/04/06.   In the early evening hours on 8/03/06, CHEMTREC was again notified by a local resident of a venting tank car at the aforementioned location. GATX 78009 was reported venting intermittently from the PRD. GATX 78009 was shipped under the same billing as GATX 93666. Local BNSF supervision was notified and GATX 78009 was then scheduled to be immediately placed into the consignee’s facility for unloading. BNSF notified the shipper to inspect all their shipments awaiting unloading at this Arizona facility. On 8/04/06, the shipper reported that the average liquid temperature of these tank cars of LPG awaiting unloading were at 101 degrees F. These tank cars were loaded at an average liquid temperature of 81 degrees F. The shipper agreed to increase the product outage for all future shipments to this Arizona location which would allow for additional temperature related product expansion without PRD release events.

column168: This tank car was reported leaking from the bottom outlet area by the trainmaster on track MCII about 12 cars deep in Johnston “C” Yard at Memphis, TN. CN HazMat Team responded and inspection revealed product coming from bottom outlet flange. All bolts on flange were tool tight. After opening and closing the bottom outlet valve several times the leak stopped. Cars were then moved to the customer a short distance away for off loading. Representative of the customer was advised of the problem with the car and not to load again and have car sent home shop for repairs or servicing to bottom cutlet flange and valves to ensure it did not leak in transportation again.

column168: A Howes Oil Company driver loaded his tanker trailer with 8500 gallons of gasoline at the Magellan Pipeline in Sioux Falls, SD. While exiting the pipeline, his tanker disconnected from the truck and caught fire. Most of the 8500 gallons burned in the fire. A small amount of gas leaked into the storm sewer system and drained into a nearby creek.     Police, fire, and containment crews were on hand in less than 5 minutes (no police report or fire report was given to Howes Oil.) The gasoline in the creek was contained and cleaned up. Testing of water showed no contaminants are present.    The total cost for cleanup, response, and property damages are not known at this time (and may not be known within the 30 day deadline for this report to be filed.) The estimated cost of loss material and carrier damage was listed in this report.
column169: It would be helpful if there were a product available that Carriers could purchase and install on either their semi-trucks or tanker trailers that would notify a driver if his trailer was not properly hooked up to the truck's fifth wheel. There appears to be a lack of back-up safety options available to Carriers in the event a trailer were to disconnect from a truck.

A hazmat shipment loaded on a pallet came in contact with an extended side pallet lock during loading, which tore a gash approx. 6 inches in length and .5 inches in height...allowing its' contents to pour out onto the a/c floor. Upon immediate discovery, the loading procedure was discontinued...the pallet removed from the a/c and a spill/clean-up group summoned to begin clean-up. The TOLUENE/METHOXYSILANE mixture immediately solidified upon contact with air which assisted in the clean-up process.
column169: Cargo handlers (vendors) will instruct their employees to check pallets for any irregularities prior to performing function-specific services ensuring contents are positioned well within the defined loading area of the pallet.  Cargo handlers (vendors) will instruct their employees that belt loaders are not to be used under any circumstances to push/move cargo pallets AND side locks are to always be in the retracted (up) position throughout the a/c prior to the commencement of loading.

A Railroad Supervisor inspected the area around the tank car and could not detect any odor.  The Railroad's Environmental Department was called to handle the matter.  The track in which the tank car was located was locked and flagged.  The manway area was inspected.  There was a small leak coming from the gauging device assembly.  The packing nut has been left loose.  The packing nut was tightened and the leak was stopped.

According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While unloading, one wet carton containing 4, .25 liter plastic bottles was discovered.  Approximately .25 liters of free product were released and were contained by the packaging.  Apparently the release was due to improper packaging.  BAX Global, Inc. personnel placed the wet carton into a salvage drum pending further instructions.  Chemtran of Houston, Texas was dispatched to perform additional cleanup.  Chemtran personnel removed the contents from the carton, cleaned and repacked for transportation.  The carton was forwarded to the consignee with the remainder of the shipment.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, BAX Global, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: On this date Roeder Cartage driver Dale Friend arrived at Marsulex, Oregon at 1610 hrs. with Spent Sulfuric Acid, 1831. He scaled in and following company policy drove to the assigned dock, that being B dock to unload. After unloading he was then instructed to go to a dock to load 99% sulfuric acid. The driver first hooked up the nitrogen line to pressure up the trailer and also he grounded the trailer for safety procedures. He then hooked up the unloading line to the trailer, opened the one unloading valve on the trailer, and then drew a sample thru the sample recovery valve. Driver then turned on unloading pump to unload. The driver has done this enough times he knows how many minutes to leave the nitrogen on arid then turn off to then start to vent trailer. This he did and in the length of time it normally takes to do this procedure he said the unloading line shook indicating the trailer was empty. He then unhooked, washed down and went to A dock to load. Driver then hooked the correct loading line, hooked vent line to vent since it is a contained unit,, reset loading meter, turned pump on. Driver then went down to change the placards when he noticed acid coming out the ‘pop off valve on top of the trailer. At this time he turned off the pump and notified Marsulex personal. Upon arrival at spill site they then observed another spill area being at the’ scrubber’ site. The scrubber had ruptured and split. Soda ash was applied to the area, 33 bags. The driver was then instructed to weigh out to see how much the trailer and truck weighed. It was found to be 81,300 lbs. His weights coming in were GROSS 73140, TARE 29400, NET 43640. The trailer is a 3600 gallon tank, when he shut off the pump it registered 713 gallons. The reason for the spill is that in the unloading procedure the driver forgot to open Marsulex line valve. NO product was pumped off. Fresh acid was loaded on top of the spent all ready in the trailer causing it to over flow thru the pressure relief valve and back up thru the venting scrubber.   EXPLAINATION;   The hose shook because when the line was hooked to the trailer there was naturally ally air trapped in the line between the trailer valve and the line valve. Trailer valve was opened and some spent acid went into unload line and compressed the air. When the trailer vented down the spent then receded back into the trailer due to equalization of pressure and the hose shook showing a sign of being empty. This total procedure took about 50 minutes between unloading and loading and the spill.   A cleanup company was called in to clean and neutralize the area which was about fifteen feet by fifteen feet. Unit was available for use the next day. NO injuries were occurred.
column169: Actions taken to prevent recurrence is that it has not been standard operating procedures to scale out for an empty or tare weight between unloading and reloading acid. ]f this had been required the driver would of noticed the difference of weight and knew something was wrong which he should have noticed when he moved the truck to change from B rack to A rack. This is now required operating procedure. Marsulex and Roeder Cartage Safety Department will soon begin coordinating refresher training on all procedures.

column168: THIS INCIDENT WAS AN UNDECLARED SHIPMENT OF A RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL SOURCE.  THE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL WAS A GE-68 SOURCE USED FOR GE DST PET SCANNER.  THE PIN SOURCE WAS SECURE IN A SHIELDED CONTAINER AND THERE WAS NO RELEASE.    ON AUGUST 3, 2006, A SEALED RADIOACTIVE SOURCE CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 18.5 MBQ GE-68 WAS DISCOVERED IN A LEAD SHIELDED CONTAINER INSIDE A MOBILE PET TRAILER THAT HAD BEEN RETURNED FROMA CUSTOMER IN NEW ORLEANS TO AK SPECIALTY VEHICLES IN CALUMET CITY, IL ON FEBRUARY 24, 2006.  THE TRAILER CAME BACK WITH THE UNDERSTANDING THAT ALL RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL HAD BEEN REMOVED BEFORE SHIPPING AS THE UNIT WAS INSPECTED PRIOR TO TRANSFER WHEN A SOURCE HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THE PET SYSTEM, BUT NO ADDITIONAL SOURCES ERE IDENTIFIED AT THE TIME.  THE TRAILER THEN SAT IN STORAGE UNTIL AUGUST, WHEN THE UNIT WAS SCHEDULED FOR REMODELING.  THE GE068 SOURCE WAS THEN DISCOVERED DURING REMODELING ON A COUNTER THAT WAS SECURED BY A METAL ROLLING DOOR.  THE SOURCE WAS IN A SHIELDED CONTAINER AND HAD NO VISIBLE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL MARKINGS.  RADIATION LEVELS ON THE SURFACEOF THE CONTAINER WERE APPROXIMATELY 1.2MR/H AND NOT CONSIDERED TO BE AN IMMEDIATE RADIOLOGICAL HAZARD.  AK THEN NOTIFIED GE THAT A SOURCE WAS PRESENT AT WHICH TIME THE SOURCE WAS SECURED AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR ITS RETURN TO THE MANUFACTURER IN ACCORDANCE WITH AGREEMENT FROM ILLINOIS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY-DIVISION OF NUCLEAR SAFETY WHO ERE NOTIFIED OF THE DISCOVERY OF THE SOURCE ON AUGUST 23,2006.
column169: A CUSTOMER RETURN PROTOCOL IS BEING ESTABLISHED TO PREVENT REOCCURRENCE OF A SIMILAR EVENT.  A CHECKLIST WILL BE PROVIDED TO THE CUSTOMER, REQUIRING CONFIRMATION THAT ANY RADIOACTIVE OR BIOHAZARD MATERIALS HAVE BEEN REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER.  THE CUSTOMER WILL HAVE TO SIGN THE CHECKLIST PROVIDING WRITTEN CONFIRMATION BEFORE THE TRAILER WILL BE SCHEDULED FOR TRANSPORT.  ADDITIONAL ACTIONS AT THE TIME OF DE-INSTALLATION WILL ALSO BE PERFORMED BYA FIELD ENGINEER TO ENSURE THAT THERE IS NO RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL ON BOARD AT THE TIME OF TRANSFER.

column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate. By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence. After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction. For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: While loading a trailer from a railcar through an unloading station and manifold, the operator noticed ammonia vapor leaking from a capped hose at an adjacent unloading station.  As he proceeded toward the station, he noticed a slight vapor cloud from the hose end.  He immediately closed the valves from the railcar and relieved pressure on the line by diverting the contents to a water-containing absorber.  He went to the adjacent unloading station and found that a valve that connects the station to the unloading manifold was 1/4 turn open. He closed the valve and the leak stopped.  The release lasted about two minutes and the release was estimated to be 15 to 20 pounds of anhydrous ammonia to the atmosphere.  No evacuations were made, no injuries were reported and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.

column168: According to the information obtained the following is known.  While the trailer was docked preparing for delivery, the doors where opened and immediately closed and refused due to a toxic odor.  Upon investigation 24, 5-gallon plastic pails were damaged due to load being improperly secured. The shipment was moved to a different location to be cleaned up and secured.  Approximately 5 gallons released on to the floor of the trailer and pavement directly under the trailer.  RMCAT Environmental Services contained and cleaned up the spill using oil dry and simply green.  After cleanup, RMCAT secured and re-palletized the load for transportation.  RMCAT placed the oil dry and debris in 1, 55 gallon recovery drum and overpacked the 24 damaged 5-gallon plastic pails in 4, 55 gallon recovery drums.  RMCAT generated a total 5, 55 gallon drums of waste to be disposed.  No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

THIS WAS NOT A LIQUID RELEASE; IT WAS A NON REPORTABLE VAPOR RELEASE.  This report is of several vapor releases due to:    3-way air valve setting (normal, not a failure, adjusted by driver by hand);    normal venting during depressurization of trailer;    possible failure of bolt to tighten seal due to bolt brace bent by consignee.    Transportation of 22 degree baume hydrochloric delivery to consignee made without problem.  Consignee attendant departed unload area.    Trailer was pressurized after hooking up to consignee tank, with 3-way valve set to vent into consignee tank and when unloading was begun, condensation of vapor became visible from exhaust hose of trailer.  Driver stopped the process immediately, hand tightened 3-way valve to the exhaust hose, began unload without additional vapor visible.    Consignee attendant returned due to visible vapor, advised driver to depressurize trailer, which released very visible vapors as is normal.  Consignee then tightened the dome bolts with heavy pipe wrench, causing one dome bolt to 'bottom out' on the dome lid brace, bending the brace.  When repressurized, consignee not satisfied with dome lid seal.  Unload stopped.
column169: As a precautionary measure the trailer is now out of service, the entire dome lid is being replaced, and the trailer will be pressure/leak tested after the relacement and before it is returned to service.

column168: On August 21, 2006, a tractor-trailer operated by KLLM Transport Services experienced a load shift. As a result one of the 55-gallon drums of resin aboard the trailer was creased and approximately 10 gallons of resin was released onto the trailer floor, and one gallon of that migrated onto the asphalt below.  At approximately 2:57 pm, KLLM Transport Services retained Cura Emergency Services (CES) to manage the environmental clean up operations. The CES incident manger contacted the driver of the vehicle to obtain additional information. The driver of the vehicle had turned the temperature of the trailer down, and placed a bucket under the trailer where the material was migrating to the asphalt. These measures prevented the material from migrating farther than it could have. Based on the information provided the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Environmental Management Services(EMS) to perform the corrective actions. The crew from EMS arrived onsite and assessed the scope of the release. The crew began corrective actions by deploying absorbent materials to the asphalt where the resin had migrated. The absorbents were worked in with brooms and placed into a drum. The material on the trailer floor had congealed due to the low temperatures. This required the response team to hand scrape the rivets on the trailer floor to remoe the gelled resin. The material was placed into the drum as well. The crew then utilized absorbent pads to remove the residue left behind from the gel. The damaged drum was over packed and placed into an over pack drum. The non-damaged drums were secured in the trailer, along with the two over pack drums.  On August 22, 2006, the driver of the tractor-trailer returned to the road after his required sleep. It was arranged for the drums to be dropped off at a facility in Des Moines, IA called Hydro-Kleen. They will processes and disposed of the two over pack drums.  Disposal Pending

column168: On August 24, 2006, at approximately 12:30 p.m. CDT, a tractor-trailer operated by KLLM Transport Services was traveling eastbound on 1-35 when the driver observed a liquid substance leaking out of the rear of the trailer. An estimated one gallon of UN1866 Polymer was leaking from a 55-gallon drum.  On August 24, 2006, at approximate 1:03 p.m. CDT, Cura Emergency Services (CES) was contacted by KLLM Transport Services to manage clean up operations following the discovery of the release. The local fire department first responded to the site and made first entry in the trailer. Fire department personnel located one 55-gallon drum of polymer resin laying on its side, leaking its contents. The drum was uprighted to stop the leakage. Based on the information given, CES retained a crew from Grones Environmental to perform a site assessment and complete clean up operations. A crew from Grones mobilized to the site and absorbed the material that had leaked out of the trailer. The drum had suffered a puncture on its side near the top of the drum. The crew placed the drum into an overpack drum before securing it back on board.

The hazardous shipment was delivered to the port marine terminal by the trucking company but the delivering documents had no indication that the shipment was hazardous.  There were no placards on the container and no hazmat billing.  The customer provided a faxed copy of the documents to our documentation department where they checked the record and discovered that the cargo was received without any hazardous indicator.  The customer was contacted to explain the regulatory requirement and the non declared shipment reporting requirement.  The customer provided a completed set of documents to cover the hazardous shipment.
column169: The container contents should be checked by the customer against all documentation prior to leaving his dock.  There should be a 24 hour requirement to allow for errors to be checked prior to the cargo being lifted to a cargo vessel.

At approximately 1045 hours, 08/18/2006 a release of Oxygen, refrigerated liquid occurred on a 3000 gallon stand tank, at the Apria Healthcare facility, 8446 Moller Road, Indianapolis, IN. Apria employee Mike Berkley was in the area and heard the release. He immediately contacted his supervisor Ryan Decker. Decker went to the stand tank and due to the amount of liquid escaping from the tank and the fog it produced deemed it unsafe for him to approach the tank to attempt to close the valves. The emergency plan was implemented. At approximately 1050 hours, notification was made to the Pike Township Fire Department, Corporate Transportation Safety Management, and facility management. The area was secured from vehicular and pedestrian traffic and an evacuation was implemented with Apria employees as well as the two adjacent businesses, I.H.I. and M.K.M. Distribution.    At approximately 1055 hours the first responders from the fire department arrived. The fire department Hazmat team took charge of the operation. They were advised that there was approximately 2500 gallons of Oxygen, refrigerated liquid in the tank. Telephonic contact was made with Matthew Nolting, MedO2, the  LOX supplier. Once the Hazmat team spoke with him they advised that the area should remain secured and the tank allowed to drain until it was empty.    At approximately 1310 hours Incident Commander Donald Blackwell advised that the oxygen content in the building were at safe levels and the evacuation was terminated. The scene was released and the fire department left the area.    Inspection of the tank revealed that a pipe fitting failed on a discharge line.    There were no injuries or collateral damage. The LOX evaporated and there was no clean up required. The stand tank was placed out of service pending repairs and inspection by the contracted maintenance/repair company.    The stand tank was manufactured by Minnesota Valley Engineering, Inc., in 1981, serial #105, National Board #4434. Maximum working pressure 50 psi.
column169: Inspection procedures are being reviewed with all facilities that have stand tanks. A review is being conducted of our internal annual inspection procedures to verify that they are adequate.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a forklift puncture, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  BAX Global Inc. will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures, in relation to blocking, bracing, and handling of freight, to all personnel.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver arrived at delivery location with a load of High Sulfur Diesel to be pumped into customer's above ground tank.  Driver verified with the customer's site manager that the product being delivered would fit in their tank within the 90% max fill capacity which is FRTL policy.  Customer signed our Product Integrity Form indicating the same.    While unloading the last compartment, the tank overfilled and product began to escape.  Driver shut down flow of product.  Approximately 20 to 30 gallons was released, but contained in the concrete containment area around the tank.  Product was cleaned up with spill pads and oil dry.
column169: Customer must keep track of fuel level in tank and be sure load will fit before accepting product.

column168: OUR VEHICLE HAD JUST LOADED AT THE RAIL TRANSFER FACILITY.  WHILE EXITING THE FACILITY THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING THROUGH THE AIR CHARGE LINE. UPON INVESTIGATION HE REALIZED THAT HE HAD LEFT THE AIRCHARGE VALVE OPEN AND PRODUCT SURGE CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO SYPHON OUT.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED. SINCE THE INCIDENT WAS IN CLOSE PROXIMITY TO OUR TERMINAL OUR PERSONNEL RESPONDED BY SPREADING SODA ASH ON THE SMALL AREA AFFECTED AND REMOVED THE MATERIAL ONCE THE PRODUCT WAS ADSORBED AND NEUTRALIZED.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS TAKEN TO THE TANKWASH AND PROPERLY DISPOSED IN THEIR SYSTEM.
column169: THIS IS A TRAINING ISSUE.  ALL DRIVERS ARE REMINDED OF THE PROVISIONS OF TITLE 49 CFR SUBPART 177.834

column168: The shipper had billed their freight as non-hazardous cleaning compounds and Aerosols, 2.2, UN1950. The freight was stacked on pallets and black shrink wrap was used. It was impossible to see the freight that was actually loaded on the pallets because of the black shrink wrap, the black shrink wrap did have the markings and labels required for the Aerosols 2.2 that were inside of the black shrink wrap but there was no indication of any other hazards inside of the shrink wrap either on the paperwork or by the markings and labels. This freight was moved by vessel on the ocean from New Jersey to Puerto Rico. Upon arrival to the terminal in Puerto Rico, a liquid was noticed leaking out of the back of the container. The container was opened and the pallets with the black shrink wrap were leaking. Suspecting that the material was non-hazardous since all the liquid on the pallets was supposed to be non-hazardous, the terminal began breaking down the skids to discover that most of the 5-gallon pails on the skid contained DOT Corrosive Liquid. A hazmat team had to be called out to the terminal to handle the clean up. In the end, none of the corrosive pails leaked, all the pails that actually leaked were documented as being the non-hazardous cleaning compounds.
column169: In numerous phone calls, emails, and faxes to the shipper since this spill, this shipper is still very unfamiliar with the requirements on shipping hazardous materials. The shipper needs to provide the required training to all hazmat employees prior to shipping hazardous materials.

column169: ON THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR), SHIPPERS ARE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF ALL HAZMAT RELEASES.  FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELEASES (AKA PACKAGE OR CLOSURE DEFECTS), WHERE POSSIBLE, SHIPPERS (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) ARE REQUESTED TO RESPOND, REPAIR AND REMEDIATE.  BY IMMEDIATELY INVOLVING THE SHIPPER, IN-DEPTH KNOWLEDGEOF THE RELEASE CAUSE IS GAINED BY THE SAME ORGANIZATION THAT CAN IMPLEMENT PROCESS CHANGES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.  AFTER EACH NAR INCIDENT, KCSR PROVIDES OUTREACH TO THE SHIPPER TO HELP INVESTIGATE ROOT-CAUSE FACTORS FOR CORRECTION.  FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELATED RELEASES, THE SHIPPER SHOUD BE CONTACTED DIRECTLY FOR DETAILS ASSOCIATED WITH ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: During delivery to our customer, IRC in Temecula, a minor spill was noticed in the carrier's trailer, UPS Freight. Approximately 3 gallons of product leaked from a plug on an unused port from the IBC. The IBC had a plastic bag on the top and the bag was stretch-wrapped to the IBC.  However, the IBC design does not allow the bag to be tight to the top and would not prevent the plug from backing out.  Since the plug was found on the floor of the trailer on arrival it is assumed that the plug backed out and fell out due to heavy vibration/movement during transit from the carrier's Rialto terminal to the final destination in Temecula.    An IRC emergency response team assembled to clean-up the minor spill. The plug cap was replaced and tightened on the IBC.
column169: Our fill operators routinely check visually to verify the plug is flush with the top of the tote. As a corrective action, we have revised our fill procedures to tighten the seal plug to the manufacturers' recommended torque spec of 10 ft/lbs on every fill.  All operators have been retrained.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While disconnecting the hose, upon completion of offloading, the free product sprayed from the hose onto the Slay Transportation Co., Inc. driver. Apparently, the hose was not properly bled, prior to disconnection, which resulted in the release of approximately 8 ounces of free product. The free product released onto the Slay Transportation Co., Inc. driver’s clothing and forearms. Upon discussion with Bayer Material Sciences, the shipper of the product, the driver washed the affected area. No free product was released to the ground. No further actions were required.
column169: In order to prevent recurrence of the incident or similar incidents, Slay Transportation Co., Inc. drivers are required to attend safety meetings. Safety meetings address such issues as handling spills, driving hazards and job specific training. Slay Transportation Co., Inc. drivers are required to attend DOT job specific training classes. Slay Transportation Co., Inc. addresses safety issues in their driver’s newsletter. Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safety guidelines to all employees.

column168: Vehicle was north bound on Hwy 95 following a recreational vehicle at approximately 45mph. When a passing lane became available, driver checked his mirrors, down shifted, and pulled out to pass. He looked left as he was changing lanes and saw a car passing at a high rate of speed. The car passed striking a guard rail causing it to spin out. The truck driver stopped rapidly causing the strapped load to shift. The bottom of the plastic drum slid over a screw in the truck bed gouging and cutting the drum. The driver noticed the leak and tipped the drum on its side to stop the release, approximately one gallon was lost.
column169: Accident was the result of unsafe passing.  The driver was cited.  Ticket 3C-0033286 state of Nevada.

column168: A sedan was stopped on the side of the west bound lane of Kaumualii Highway.  The Gas Company, LLC (TGC) tanker truck was travelling in the west bound lane of the highway.  As the TGC tanker truck approached the area near the sedan, the sedan entered the highway from the side of the roadway.  The TGC tanker truck applied its brakes but could not stop in time and collided with the sedan.  The sedan crossed the east bound lane of the highway, hit a tree, then came to rest.    Damage to the TGC tanker truck was limited to the front section and there was no release of liquefied petroleum gas that was being transported.
column169: The Gas Company's initial investigation did not come up with any substantial recommendations or actions to prevent recurrence.  The Gas Company will continue to evaluate.

column168: DART TRUCKING COMPANY, INC. DRIVER TRANSPORTED A LOAD OF 87 DRUMS OF HAZARDOUS AND NON-HAZARDOUS WASTES FROM VEOLIA IN PHILADELPHIA TO VEOLIA IN WEST CARROLLTON, OH. UPON ARRIVAL IN WEST CARROLLTON THE LOAD WAS TO BE UNLOADED WHEN A SMALL SPILL WAS INDENTIFIED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.    NO MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED THE VAN TRAILER. VEOLIA CONDUCTED THE CLEAN UP OF THE MATERIAL AND THE EQUIPMENT, AND DETERMINED THAT 2 GALLONS HAD SPILLED.
column169: DART TRUCKING COMPNAY, INC. DRIVERS UNDERGO A STRINGENT TRAINING PROGRAM WHICH DETAILS THE EXAMINATION OF DRUMS AND CONDUCTING REGULAR LOAD CHECKS TO WATCH FOR SPILLS OR POTENTIAL INCIDENTS.    THIS PARTICULAR DRUM DID NOT SHOW SIGNS OF POSSIBLE FAILURE. HOWEVER, UPON MOVEMENT FROM TRANSPORTATION, THE SEAM FAILED.

column168: DRIVER LOCKED UNLOADING DOWNSPOUT AND HOSE TO CUSTOMER TANK.  BECAUSE OF THE WAY THE UNIT ENTERED SLOTS, UNLOADING CONNECTION WAS ON OPPOSITE SIDE OF TRAILER FROM THE OPERATIONAL VALVES.  WHEN PRODUCT WAS TURNED ON, PRESSURE BLEW DOWNSPOUT OFF OF TANK FILL PIPE.  (CONNECTOR WAS NOT PROPERLY LOCKED.)  DRIVER DID NOT SEE DISCONNECT IMMEDIATELY AND LOST 660 GALLONS OF GASOHOL.  TOTAL SPILL TIME APPROXIMATELY ONE MINUTE.  DIKING WAS IMPLOYED, FIRE DEPARTMENT CALLED, DUTY OFFICER NOTIFIED, ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY CALLED.  SEWERS FLUSHED AND SPILL CLEANED ACCORDING TO MPCA STANDARDS.
column169: ALL DRIVERS WERE REMINDED TO CHECK LOCK MECHANISM OF DOWN SPOUTS AND PROPERLY POSITION EQUIPMENT TO UNLOAD.

column168: WAS CALLED TO A LEAKING CORROSIVE HAZMAT IN THE UNLOAD. WHILE WEARING MY PPE I RESPONDED TO THE PACKAGE USING MY DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE DAMAGED CONTENTS AND DEBRIS WERE DISPOSED OF VIA THE DMP PROCESS. THE REMAINING CLEAN INTACT BOTTLES WERE SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER IN A SALVAGE DRUM. ONCE ALL WAS COMPLETED I DECONTAMINATED MY PPE.

PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING ON THE SORT AISLE.  DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEETS WERE FOLLOWED.  ENTIRE CONTENTS AND CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING DMP PROCEDURES.  ALL PPE NEEDED WAS USED.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN A MAJOR, 1 VEHICLE ACCIDENT WHICH INVOLVED A ROLLOVER OF OUR EQUIPMENT.  THE DRIVER SAID THAT THE RIGHT SIDE TIRES GOT OFF, ON THE SOFT SHOULDER OF THE INTERSTATE.  THE DRIVER SAID THAT HE TRIED TO GET IT BACK UP ON THE INTERSTATE AND OVERCORRECTED, CAUSING THE TRACTOR AND THE TRAILER TO ROLLOVER 1 ½ TIMES. column168: A BNSF switch crew reported GATX 137 with product slosh from the top fitting area of this tank car during switching movement in the rail yard. Movement was stopped and GATX 137 was cordoned off in the rail yard. BNSF contract responders inspected GATX 137 and reported finding the fill hole gasket was misaligned, as part of the gasket was hanging over the fill hole nozzle lip. This gasket misalignment prevented a good seal. Responders removed the fill hole seal (0014087), loosened the fill hole securement on the cover and properly aligned and reseated the fill hole gasket. After the fill hole gasket was in its correct position, the fill hole cover was closed and resecured. Contractor response concluded by 2220 hrs, CDT, 8/24/06. The next day, spillage on the shell of GATX 137 was neutralized and cleaned off in the rail yard. No product was reported impacting the ground.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: A BNSF employee in the railyard reported GATX 201840 emanating an intermittent ‘hissing’ noise and GATX 201840 was cordoned off in the railyard. No product odor was detected and GATX 201840 was carefully isolated in the railyard for further inspection. BNSF contract responders reported that the Midland 280.5 psi pressure relief device/valve (PRD) was activated and relieving internal pressure via expelling part of the internal nitrogen blanket inside GATX 201840. It was decided to off load some product to reduce the internal pressure. Product inside GATX 201840 was reduced and transferred into an appropriate tanker truck without incident. Transfer was concluded by 0100 hrs. CDT, 8/26/06. At the start of the transfer the outage measured 16 inches at 260 psi. After the transfer was completed the outage was measured at 46 1/2 inches at 200 psi. The PRD reseated to the closed position during the initial phase of the product transfer. With the PRD reseated and product off load completed, GATX 201840 was released to proceed to its destination. The tanker truck was delivered to the consignee on 8/26/06. The shipper related that at origin the outage measured 19 1/4 inches at 209 psi. The shipper will have the PRD inspected to determine cause of the PRD activation at the lower psi level.

column168: A BNSF conductor walking along side of his train after closing a switch, noticed product dripping down the side of entrained ACFX 73462. The BNSF train crew setout ACFX 73462 in the siding at the discovery location for mitigation response and investigation. BNSF responders inspected ACFX 73462 the morning of 8/29 after placing a catch receptacle under this tank car. Responders reported finding the closure cap to the liquid eduction line loose and it was tool tightened slowing the leak. BNSF contract responders arrived afterwards and inspected the closure cap finding no sealing material on either the closure cap or eduction pipe threads. Contract responders applied Teflon tape onto the threads, reapplied the closure cap and tool tightened the cap. No further leakage evident after closure cap secured. Responders then checked the fill hole. The fill hole securement and its gasket were good. The product outage was checked and it was approximately six inches which equated to a little more than a 2% outage. A vacuum truck that was ordered previously to this location (in case product reduction was necessary) was not used and released after responders concluded that ACFX 73462 was not overfilled. The frangible disc was also checked and it was intact, but the rupture disc housing cover hinge was broken and BNSF mechanical personnel were informed of this defect. Contract responders neutralized all spillage on the shell of ACFX 73462 and also any ground impact areas that were discovered. Contract response concluded on 8/29/06 and ACFX 73462 was released to proceed to its destination.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER'S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT RELATES TO THE TOTAL SECUREMENT AND MECHANICAL FITNESS OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS.

column168: A BNSF road switcher pulling railcars from an industry track to move them towards the main track siding to switch them, reported UTLX 200589 splashed product from the manway area during a coupling event. The product splashed onto the tank car shell and the ground. The ground impact of the product resulted in a small flare-up of flame atop the ground which soon burned out. Railcar movement was immediately stopped when the BNSF crew noticed the flame flare-up on the ground. The local F.D. was called to eliminate fire threats and monitor the remediation process. A BNSF mechanical-hazardous material responder inspected UTLX 200589 and reported finding all 8 manway securement swing bolts hanging (not applied). The BNSF responder applied and properly tool tightened all the manway securement bolts. The liquid eduction line valve was closed, but an unloading fitting (reducer) was still applied on this valve and the protective housing cover was down (not closed). Responder removed this fitting, flanged capped the eduction line and closed the protective housing cover over this valve. Apparently, the unloader for the consignee was in the process of unloading product from UTLX 200589 and failed to resecure the manway cover when the unloading process was stopped or interrupted. The industry track that UTLX 200589 was pulled from was not blue flagged. Securement of UTLX 200589 was completed by 0045 hrs. CDT, 8/31/06. UTLX 200589 was returned to the unloading facility.

column168: Two of our employees were sent out to assist one of our drivers with safely maneuvering her tractor within tight confines of the consignee's facility.  When they arrived at the facility they donned the facility-required PPE which included Nomex suit, hard hat, safety glasses and safety shoes. By time they located our driver, she was already at the customer's tank and was completing the setup to connect to the customer's tank.  Our two employees did not intend to participate in the unload procedure.  They were talking and were unaware that our driver had opened the valves on the cargo tank to start the transfer of product.  Before our two employees had cleared the immediate area, and while one of them had his back to the unload operation, product escaped from an open bleeder valve on the discharge side of the product pump and hit our employee on the right calf.  Our employee was immediately taken to the shower. Quick action resulted in being treated and receiving a full-release from the hospital.
column169: The driver did not follow prescribed procedures.  She failed to verify that the bleeder valve on the product pump was closed before opening the trailer valve.  Her actions will be addressed by her leadership and loss prevention teams.

column168: After a BNSF intermodal train arrived at the BNSF intermodal facility, intermodal trailer SFTZ 220569 was observed with an unknown substance under the trailer and atop the intermodal flatcar deck it was riding. SFTZ 220569 was deramped and immediately taken to the containment area. Plastic sheeting was placed under SFTZ 220569. Inspection by BNSF contract responders found lading stacked to the trailer’s ceiling and much of the lading had to be removed to get to the leak source. Responders found seven 5 gallon poly pails of a corrosive catalyst had been damaged during a load shift. The pails were loaded on a pallet with several heavy industrial type vehicle tires placed unsecured atop this pallet. During transit movement the heavy tires shifted causing the pallet of pails to collapse and topple over. Of the seven damaged pails, four were dented and cracked at the pail bottom and lost all product inside the pails. The other three pails were dented but did not leak. Also, one 55 gallon drum of non-hazardous resin was found and had lost a small amount of product due to a stress fracture from drum rotation during transit. The lading inside the trailer was sorted and decontaminated and this lading was picked-up by the consignee (UPS Freight). The intermodal rail flatcar deck and the inside of SFTZ 220569 were cleaned. All damaged pails and the 55 gallon drum were placed inside 85 gallon recovery drums and returned inside SFTZ 220569 along with the remainder of the lading that wasn’t impacted by any spillage. All the waste materials were bagged and also placed inside SFTZ 220569.  During the initial phases of discovery and clean-up, one box of Sodium Chlorate, UN 1495 was found inside SFTZ 220569 by a ERA Inspector and the contract responders. This package was listed as a Limited Quantity on the shipping papers found inside  the trailer, but was not included on the rail waybill. A separate BNSF DOT 5800.1 report (06-0821-01) initiated for this  Undeclared Shipment.

column168: On 8/23/06, shipper notified BNSF that tank car PROX 29050 on hand at the BNSF Pasco railyard was overfilled. The shipper also requested a FRA Movement Approval for PROX 29050. A joint BNSF/FRA inspection of PROX 29050 on 8/25 revealed that the ‘Water Capacity in US Gallons’ was not marked on either tank head. Also, product dampness and a slight product odor were observed around the 2-inch vapor valve closure pipe plug. The BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder tool tightened the vapor valve closure plug three full turns which eliminated the product weeping from this orifice. The minor product spillage evaporated. On 8/29/06, excess product in PROX 29050 was off loaded into a tanker truck without further incident. Product transfer was completed around 1900 hrs. PDT, 8/29/06.

column168: At approximately 7:30 a.m. the driver reported a release of crude oil to his immediate supervisor.  The cause was the mechanical failure of a blown gasket on the suction line of the truck.  The driver immediately shut off the valves and put down booms and pads to contain the spill.  The spill crossed the road on Highway 1087 into the ditch line.  Two Refinery personnell in the vacinity were dispatched with cleanup supplies that they put down as soon as they arrived onsite.  Somerset Environmental Services, Inc. was dispatched at 7:50 a.m. to respond for cleanup.  SES personnell arrived onsite at 10:00 a.m. and immediately began putting down more oil dry and and sweeping the road getting it dry and sweeping up the oil dry from the road.  Smith Oil Field Services arrived on the site at 10:35 a.m. with a dump truck load of clean rock. They immediately began cleaning the loading area and shoulder of the road and loading the contaminated dirt and rock into the dump truck. There was 8.22 ton of soil and rock disposed of at Laurel Ridge Landfill.  Seed and straw was spread on the edge of the road way for reseeding the excavated area.  The State Highway department put down sand and swept it off the road after SOS had cleaned the shoulder of the road.
column169: South Kentucky Purchasing has conducted an interview with the driver to determine the cause of the accident.  The driver was not at fault.  It was determined that the drivers should be trained in determining when to report a spill immediately to the proper authorties therfore, making them first responders.  In this case the driver followed the procedures as he was instructed but someone had already reported the spill to the state officials before SKP had a chance to do so.

column168: The accident occurred at approximately 10:05 am on August 26, 2006. The gasoline transport overturned while entering 1440 off the Hwy 70 off ramp. Fire Departments and EMS personnel were notified and on the scene by approximately 10:20 am. Pollution Management, Inc., the company used by B-B Oil Company to respond to environmental cleanup issues, was contacted and on the scene to begin to secure the area by 10:45 am. The gasoline tanker was on it’s side and leaking gasoline and diesel fuel from the manhole covers on top of the tanker. Pollution Management, Inc. burmed the area with dirt around the tanker to confine the leaking product. Another carrier was brought in to off load the gasoline and diesel fuel that remained on the tanker.
column169: B—B Oil Company will continue to train it’s drivers with regard to safety; stressing the Federated Insurance Training Program, “Point of No Return”, and concerning over-turned vehicles.

column168: PKG SENT THROUGH SORT SYSTEM: WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING ON BELT: RESPONDER PLACED IN SPILL TRAY AND REMOVED PKG TO DMP FOR PROCESSING:
PACKAGE WAS FOUND WHEN RESPONDING TO ANOTHER LEAKER ON THE SAME TRUCK.  DAMAGE WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE PSC AREA BY DESIGNATED RESPONDERS FOR PROCESSING THROUGH THE DMP.
WAS CALLED TO  A LEAKER ON M-1 FOUND THE CAGE AND NOTICED SMALL AMOUNT OF DAMPNESS ON THE SIDE OF PACKAGE. I THEN PICKED UP PACKAGE AND RETURNED WITH IT TO THE PROCESSING AREA.

I RESPONDED TO THE SPILL WEARING ALL PPE, I IDENTIFIED THE SPILL AS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID FROM THE DOT DIAMOND LABEL AND THE HAZMAT SHIPPIN PAPERS.  USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID, I PLACED THE SPILL IN A LINED SPILL TRAY AND ENSURED THERE WAS NO RESIDUE LEFT OVER BEFORE TRANSPORTING THE PACKAGE TO THE REWRAP CENTER.  THE DAMAGED PORTION WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP. THERE WAS NO SALVAGABLE PORTION TO BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: On August 30, 2006 at approximately 5:00 AM EDST, a Gambill Oil Company truck and gasoline tanker was enroute from West Jefferson, NC to make a delivery of approximately 9,200 gallons of unleaded gasoline to JoJa's Superette in Lenoir, NC.  The driver was traveling north on NC Hwy 27 near Lincolnton, NC when the truck left the road surface on the right side after rounding a curve, collided with a utility pole, overturned, caught fire and exploded, causing release of the gasoline.  No other vehicles were involved in the accident.  Local Lincoln County emergency agencies responded to the accident site, contained the fuel spill, and extinguished the burning wreckage which was totaled.  Excavation of approximately 1757 tons of contaminated soils from property oweners affected began on September 6 and were disposed at Environmental Soils facility in Lattimore, NC.

Driver was traveling north on State Road 63. He had nodded of while driving and as he became aware again he had crossed center line. While crossing center line he had hit a trailer being pulled by a pick-up going south bound. As driver tried to correct his tractor and tanker it went into a roll-over one and one half times and the tanker ended upside down. The tanker was compromised and lost the fuel that was present in the tanks.
column169: As of September 30, 2006 we have initiated a safety meeting oriented around this accident. Present will be the State Police to discuss safe driving. Also present will be the driver that was in the accident on August 22, 2006 to speak first hand as to what can happen in a split second and how important it is to be aware of your present situation physical and mental. Billy Guy from Federated Insurance will also be present to discuss fall driving with rain and leaves on the road. He will also address the recent accident and measure on how to prevent this from happening again. All drivers will be present along with Carl Bose head of Operations and Jim Owen President of S & B Transportation, Inc.

column168: At approximately 1600 hours, 8-22-05 a D cylinder failed during the transfill process at the Apria Healthcare Boothwyn, PA transfill facility. The valve and cylinder parted resulting in an unknown amount of oxygen, compressed being released.     Apria Healthcare Transfill Technician Santana Robinson was operating the transfill process and had just completed his leak and temperature check, the pressure was slightly over 1500 psi when he heard an explosion. John Woodall, Senior Transfill Technician beat him to the controls and immediately shut down the fill process. Once the pressure was shut off and the separated pig tail stopped flopping around they proceeded to start closing the valves on the remaining cylinders.     As they were closing the valves they found that a D tank, which was filling on the third row from the top of the rack, had separated from the pigtail and was on the floor. The cylinder was found on the floor on the opposite side of the room from where it had been on the rack. The valve was not in the cylinder when found. The valve was found on the floor with the quick-connect still attached. A cinder block on the wall next to the fill rack showed evidence of where the cylinder impacted and on the drywall on the opposite wall was dented. The bottom of the cylinder was buckeled, where it would have hit the cinder block wall. Placing a D tank against the dented drywall, the dent is consistent with the valve not being attached to the cylinder when it hit. The cylinder and valve were quarantined.    The cylinder that failed was part of a shipment of new cylinders that had just been received. The remaining cylinders from the shipment were blown down and placed back in the shipping box and quarantined.    The incident resulted in an unknown amount of oxygen, compressed being released. There were no injuries or damage other than to the walls.
column169: The failed cylinder and valve were sent to RSI Associates, LLC, 1652 Victory Court, Prospect, KY for examination. The report of the finding by Garland Scot will be forwarded to Pacific Cylinders (The Respiratory Group) and to Wayne Chaney, U.S. DOT, PHMSA upon receipt.    The incident was reported to the manufacture, Pacific Cylinders (The Respiratory Group), who has initiated an investigation of their processes in an attempt to identify the cause of the accident.

column168: ***Incident was not an equipment failure; incident was operator error, failure to follow corporate loading/unloading protocol.*** On 08/29,2006, driver was loading 24-gravity crude oil at the Coyote Lease. Driver was loading on the curb side of tanker. Upon commencing the tanker pump, driver enters his vehicle to complete paperwork. At some point, the driver notices crude flowing on the ground surface past his truck. He exits the cab and shuts off pump. Crude was flowing out the vapor tube on the downhill side of tanker (flood loading) . Driver notifies Brietburn Energy site personnel of the release. Brietburn immediately dispatches a backhoe to the scene and evaluates the size an impacted areas. Brietburn determines the spill is large and requires outside resources to assist with containment and remediation. Brietburn implements their SPCC plan and notifies their spill response contractor to respond and assist. Upon further evaluation, crude has entered into the onsite storm drain and is found in the flood control channel 1.5 miles down stream from where the incident occurred. A dump truck load of sand is placed at this location to stop the spread and Brietburn dispatches two vacuum trucks to the location for crude recovery. At 1200 hours, private response company (Patriot Environmental) arrives at the spill location.  ***See Attached Sheet for Additional Information***
column169: Flying J Transportation immediately conducted an investigation as to the cause of release. The transportation driver violated the following corporate policies: 1) Violated loading procedures (Flood loading of tank); 2) Violation of DOT and EPA regulations (Failure to connect vapor recovery hose) and 3) Violation of DOT regulations (Failure to monitor equipment and vehicle during loading operations). Flying J Transportation has a strict policy for failure follow loading and unloading policies. Each driver is trained and tested in these procedures.    Due to this incident, all bulk drivers will be refreshed on corporate policies and procedures for loading and unloading. They will be advised to the type of damages (both environmental and financial) caused by the lack of following those put in place to prevent such accidents from occurring.    Based on site photographs, the spread of this spill could have been prevented if the site engineered more efficient and/or had spill control devices in and around the loading areas.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELLING ON A DIRT ROAD DELIVERING CHEMICAL TREATMENTS TO OIL WELLS   AS HE CAME UP OVER A SMALL RISE HE SAW A POTHOLE IN THE ROAD AT THE BOTTOM OF THE RISE. THE HOLE WAS APPROXIMATELY 6 FT. WIDE, 3 FT. LONG, & 4—6 INCHES DEEP. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY LET UP ON THE GAS BUT COULD NOT SLOW ENOUGH BEFORE HITTING THE POTHOLE. CONTACT WITH THE POTHOLE SENT THE TRUCK OFF THE ROAD TO THE RIGHT. WHEN THE TIRES CAUGHT TRACTION ON THE ROAD SHOULDER, THE TRUCK SLOWLY ROLLED TO THE RIGHT SIDE, LANDING UPSIDE DOWN. THE 60—GAL CHEMICAL TANK ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRUCK BED SPLIT AT A SEAM & A FIT DNG WAS KNOCKED )FF, ALLOWING THE CONTENTS TO LEAK ON THE GROUND. A TOTAL OF ABOUT 33 GAL. SPILLED. IT TO 3 HRS. TO RIGHT THE TRUCK. THE SPILL WAS DIKED WITH DIRT TO PREVENT THE SPREAD & THE SCENE AS SECURED BY COUNTY EMPLOYEES. COLORADO STATE TROOPER RABE RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. A REPORT WAS TELEPHONED TO NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER BECAUSE RQ (100 LBS) OF MATERIAL WAS SPILLED. CUSTOM ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OF COLORADO SPRINGS WAS CONTRACTED TO REMEDIATE THE SPILL. DRIVER SUFFERED MINOR SCRAPES & CONTINUED WORKING THAT AFTERNOON. NO CHEMICAL EXPOSURE OCCURRED TO ANYONE. NO WILDLIFE WAS AFFECTED.

Plains truck driver was traveling west on US 190 when he fell asleep at the wheel, drifted off the roadway, and rolled the truck and trailer combination 540° into the north barrow ditch. The rollover ended with the truck/trailer coming to rest on the passenger side. At the time of discovery by the Texas Department of Public Safety, immediate rescue of the driver was accomplished; the driver was transported from the scene by ambulance due to injuries. The cargo tank rupture allowed crude oil to leak onto the barrow ditch area of the roadway. The Big Lake, TX Fire Department HazMat team contained the spill using containment booms, absorbents and soil. Duration of the spill was approximately one hour. The cargo tank rupture was a circumferential break in the upper passenger side quadrant of the tank shell, approximately 10’ forward of the rear bulkhead, approximately 18” in length, and 1” in width at its widest point.  Please see attached photographs for additional description.

column168: 1. Residue railcar was placed at loading spot.  2. Dome of railcar was opened.  3. A slight hissing noise was detected.  4. It was found that there was a slight leak coming from under the pressure relief device ( PRD ) around the gasket surface.   5. Attempts were made to tighten the bolts securing the PRD, but attempts failed to completely stop leak.  6. A leak repair clamp was installed on the PRD and leak was stopped.   7. Railcar was made gas free.  8. PRD was removed to examine the gasket and gasket surface. It was found that the gasket was slightly cracked.  9. New gasket was installed.
column169: 1. Records were examined from previous PRD repair.  2. All specifications were in order. All torque specs were correct and correct gasket had been installed.   3. All shop personnel at the repair shop where the last PRD repair was performed were retrained on changing out and inspecting gaskets for these specific PRD gaskets.

column168: A BNSF audit of hazardous material incidents revealed an incident that occurred on 8/09/06 in the state of Washington that was inadvertently not previously reported:  A Skagit County Fire District official reported to CHEMTREC that IJTLX 202080 was leaking product from the top fitting area. Shortly thereafter, shipper and Union Tank Car (UTC) representatives responded and were at the incident site. Responders broke the seal on the valve protective housing cover to inspect the top fittings. The inspection revealed that the leak source was the 3-inch top loading valve/threaded liquid valve that was cross-threaded on its threaded pipe nipple. Responders relieved the internal pressure within this tank car and the product release ebbed. The liquid valve was tool tightened 1/4 turn to end the product release. The product outage within UTLX 202080 was checked and deemed appropriate. Shipper responders began remediation of all spillage. The UTC responder removed the liquid valve and recut the pipe nipple threads that were galled. The liquid valve was inspected and deemed mechanically fit. Teflon tape was applied to the newly rethreaded pipe nipple and a new liquid valve was applied and tool tightened. UTLX 202080 was returned to the origin shipper facility to perform a thorough inspection all other valves and fittings prior to releasing it in transportation.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: SUNDAY NIGHT ON AUGUST 20, 2006, WHILE SWITCHING IN TRACK 014 A SWITCHMAN, WORKING FOR THE PTRA, STATED HE WAS OVERCOME BY FUMES FROM A CAR OF RESIDUE CHLORINE WHICH WAS IN TRACK 012.  THIS WAS IN THE P.T.R.A.'S NORTH YARD IN HOUSTON, TEXAS.  THE YARDMASTER , IN CONJUNCTION WITH THE TRAINMASTER ON DUTY, CALLED FOR EMERGENCY ASSISTANCE.  THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPT WAS FIRST TO ARRIVE AND ASSISTED IN REMOVING THE SWITCHMAN FROM THE AREA.  HOUSTON HAZMAT ARRIVED AND FOUND THAT THERE WAS SOME SMALL AMOUNT OF CHLORINE VAPOR LEAKING SOMEWHERE FROM UNDER THE VALVE COVER, THEY THROUGHT IT MIGHT BE LEAKING FROM THE BASE PLATE.  THE HAZMAT SUPERVISOR ALLOWED THAT THE CAR COULD BE MOVED BACK TO THE SHIPPER FOR FURTHER EVALUATION.  CAR WAS SPOTTED BACK AT DXI AT 06:30 08-21-06.
column169: SHIPPERS OF CHLORINE SHOULD HAVE PROCEDURES IN PLACE TO CHECK WITH DEVICES FOR LEAKS, EVEN ON RESIDUE CARS.  SHIPPERS SHOULD HAVE ALL REQUIRED CERTIFICATION AND TRAINING FOR ALL EMPLOYEES.  THIS PARTICULAR TANK CAR WAS PLACED IN OUR NORTH YARD TRACK AND WAS NOT DISTURBED FOR AT LEAST FOUR DAYS.  THE NIGHT THE LEAK WAS DETECTED THERE WAS NO WIND AT ALL AND EVIDENTLY A POCKET OF GAS VAPOR WAS ALLOWED TO FORM.  IF THE SHIPPER HAD DETECTED A VAPOR LEAK WHILE USING DETECTION DEVICES THIS INCIDENT COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED.

column168: Incident Report  Aqua Ammonia Spill at Airgas Palmerton Facility  8-21-2006      Aug. 21, 2006 I was loading the last truck of the day at approximately 5:15 PM. As the truck was being loaded I did the normal end of day shutdown checks then went to the office to get driver Dave Debone directions for his next day’s delivery. I was also training a new employee, Bill Sittler, who began asking some questions about the internet training he was undergoing. Since I had been on duty for more than 11 hours with no help and had done the end of day routine, I forgot that there was a truck being loaded and left the facility to go home. This occurred due to fatigue. At 11:45 PM  8-21  I received a phone call from Preston Grow of Horsehead Corp. secutrity. He stated Ernie Miller of  Horsehead Corp. detected strong ammonia odors from the Airgas facility. At 12:15 AM I arrived at the facility to investigate. I discovered strong odors, a running loading pump and a spill under the the truck I was loading the previous day. I then notified regional manager Tom Hobaugh.  The truck was overfilled and product discharged through the pressure relief valve. Later calculations determined that 3900 gallons of aqua ammonia where spilled to the ground.  I began fogging the area with water to bring down the odors so the pump could be shut down and secure the affected area.  When ordors where at an acceptable level and I could reach the office,  approximately 1 AM,  I made reporting calls to the LEPC, SERC and NRC agencies.  I informed LEPC that no emergency sevices were needed and the situation was under control.  Some time later James Kunkle of  DEP and Rory Koons of the Aquashicola fire dept arrived.  There was concern ammonia may have gotten to the Aquashicola Creek.  Rory Koons tested Airgas outfall with litmus paper and stated the results were negative.  Butch Kocher and myself tested the outfall on  8-22-06 and also got negative test results. I was visited by Scott Confer of DEP on  8-22-06 to discuss the situation.  He stated we should test the outfall each day for 2 weeks and report the results to him.     Recommendations:   1. Proper shift coverage of two employees per shift for plant operations as has been practiced for the past 12 years will greatly reduce the possibility of future incidents.    2. Modern programmable instrumentation would prevent overfilling of vessels.      Gene Yanick  08/24/2006
column169: Recommendations:   1. Proper shift coverage of two employees per shift for plant operations as has been practiced for the past 12 years will greatly reduce the possibility of future incidents.    2. Modern programmable instrumentation would prevent overfilling of vessels.

column168: During hook up of teh railcar for loading, the liduid hose from the shore tank was correctly hooked up the the bottom railcar loading connection.  The vapor line was inadvertantly hooked up to the top liquid loading connection.  While loading the railcar the pressure in the railcal pushed furfural up the drop tub adn out the top liquid connection.  The flexible vapor hose (incorrectly hooked up to the top liquid line filled with furfural and eventually failed.  Furfual drained from the vapor hose and continued to leak out of teh top connection of the railcar until the operator closed teh valve.    The furfural was spilled into a contained area of the loading facility.  In house responders used water spray to suppress vapors and washed the spilled material into the Odfjell enclosed wastewater system.
column169: The operator performing the transfer was a trainee operator being supervised by a senior operator.  The railcar in question was the third car this operator had done that night.  This particular railcar arrived with a slightly different top fitting configuration which the trainee had not encountered before.    All operators are re-trained on the many different types of railcar adn truck configurations that may be ensountered.      All trainee transfer line ups must be inspected by a senior operator prior to the start of the transfer.

column168: Switching crew discovered car leaking at 0240 on 8-5-06 in TASD North yard from the top when car was in motion and noticed smell. Crew notified TASD Yardmaster Lott and left car in North 15 track. I arrived at 0250 and knocked off crew. Car remained in North 15 track. I then notified Al. State Docks Protection Dept. of situation. I arrived at yard office and the Yardmaster Lott called emergency contact number on waybill at 0320 and spoke with Mr. Tom Flores ( report # 0852006018). Yardmaster Lott was contacted by BASF Co., David Darnell @0410 and stated he would contact local emergency response contractor. SWS of Pensacola Fl. was contacted and dispatched to scene and arrived at 0630. I met with Butch Warden of SWS and he explained to me that a nut and bolt had deteriorated on top flange of car.. He replaced seal on air inlet and nut and bolt. Job was completed at 0800. Very little product leaked down side of car and was cleaned by SWS employees.
column169: Better inspections of cars at plants before and after loading.

column168: Shipment arrived in Tampa on 13Aug under AWB 125-18050152. Shipment was listed as personal effects and placed on hold by U.S Customs for inspection. Upon inspection of cargo by U.S Customs, they found one fibreboard box containing 2 car batteries. U.S Customs brought this to my attention. I then notified Jeff Lyter, Air General Director of Safety and Security, Neil Burge, British Airways Area Customer Service Manager and Jim McCaffrey, British Airways VP Safety and Compliance.   I then left several messages with the FAA office in MIA to report what we had found. Special Agent Mark Gentile of the FAA office in Orlando made a visit to our facility. I explained the details and he took copies of all the paperwork regarding this shipment and also took pictures. He then said he would follow up on it and that I could forward the rest of the shipment to its final destination of Atlanta, GA.  The batteries in question are still located at British Airways Cargo in Tampa.
column169: All Dangerous Goods should be declared at station of origin.

column168: A Veolia ES Technical Solutions, L.L.C. driver was traveling southbound in route to a hazardous waste disposal facility in Peoria, IL when he was pulled over by a police car. The police officer alerted our driver that the lugger box he was transporting was leaking. After assessing the situation, it was determined that during transport, liquid had separated from the sludge material that was being transported. The liquid material then worked its way out of the lugger box between the small gap of the tarp and the top of the box. As the material made its way out, it dripped down the side of the lugger box and onto the bed of the truck.    The material being transported in the lugger box was pickling bath sludge from the production of stainless steel that carried an F006 EPA hazardous waste code. The waste is profiled as containing zero free liquids.    The driver contacted his dispatcher and the transportation manager. Calls were made to both the National Response Center (NRC case # 808854) and the WDNR spill hotline.    A Veolia response team was then dispatched to assist the driver. Once onsite, the response team pumped all free liquids from the lugger box into a tanker truck. Oil dry was then added to the lugger box to absorb any additional liquids that might separate while in transit. In addition, all free liquid was wiped from the side of the lugger box and truck bed. The debris on the ground was also absorbed and swept up with all solids being placed back into the lugger box.    Although it is difficult to determine the exact amount of material that was released, we have estimated that a maximum of 5 gallons of liquid spilled from the lugger box. It is believed that the actual amount spilled was considerably less. Because of this uncertainty, Veolia ES took a conservative approach and a call was made to the NRC because the RQ for F006 is 10 pounds.
column169: To prevent any recurrences, future shipments of this material will be checked for liquids prior to loading and shipping.

REEDER SPOKE WITH THE SHIPPER WHO ADVISED THAT THE MOST LIKELY CAUSE WAS THE PRESSURE BUILDING VALVE WAS PARTIALLY OPEN.  REEDER CLOSED THE VALVE ABOUT 3/4 TURN THEN TIGHTENED THE PACKING ABOUT 1/2 TURN.  THE RELEASE STOPPED AND PRESSURE INT HE TANK BEGAN TO DROP.  TANK WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT.

column58: O-Ring or Seals; Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing; Valve Seat
column168: On Monday August 07, 2006 at 2223 hours Toby Trevett, Special Agent Hazmat, was notified by Brad Hoksch, MYO in Avondale, LA., that a carman inspecting # 3 track on the West end of the yard reported an ammonia odor from PLMX 135277. Trevett responded and detected the same odor in the vicinity of the tank car.     Trevett contracted US Environmental Service, Inc., a Union Pacific contractor,   to respond to Avandale yard to assist.     At approximately 2350 hours, US Environmental Services personnel arrived and   inspected tank car PLMX 135277. They discovered that it was not leaking. However, the tank car was coupled to PLMX 135528, which was leaking vapor from the pressure relief device. A pressure gauge was placed on a device and it tested at 100 Lbs. of pressure. Further inspection determined that the 0-Rings were deteriorated. US Environmental personnel changed the 0-rings and secured the tank car from further leak.     Trevett released the car for transportation to shop for repairs. Tank car shipped under movement approval FRA -   06080212.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: AS RENE HERNANDEZ WAS UNLOADING THE PALLET OF PAINT, HE HAD HIS FORK AT AN ANGLE WHICH WENT THROUGH THE BOTTOM BOARDS OF THE PALLET. THAT CAUSED A BOX ON THE BOTTOM OF THE STACK TO GET PUNCTURED.
column169: THERE WERE TWO INSTANCES OF NEGLIGENCE WHICH HAD CAUSED THIS SPILL. ONE WAS THE LOADER MISJUDGED THE ANGLE OF THE PALLET. IN ADDITION, IT APPEARS THAT THE PALLET WAS DOUBLE STACKED ON AN UNEVEN SURFACE, WHICH LED THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR TO MISJUDGE THE ANGLE. GENERALLY, PALLETS OF PAINT AND OTHER HAZ-MAT SHOULD NOT BE STACKED, ESPECIALLY ON UNSECURE AND/OR UNEVEN SURFACES.
