column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED BOX WAS HELD DUE TO A STRONG FUEL TYPE OF ODOR   ASSOCIATED WITH IT. UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THE BOX CONTAINED A   GENERATOR WHICH APPEARED TO HAVE ONCE CONTAINED SOME FUEL. THE SHIPPER WAS   CONTACTED AND ADVISED THAT THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN HELD REGARDING THIS REPORTED ODOR   AT 10 AM ON FRIDAY AUGUST 18, 2006. THE MSP/FAA WAS NOTIFIED BY VOICEMAIL AT 10:35   THAT THIS PACKAGE WAS BEING HELD FOR THEIR INVESTIGATION. A RETURN PHONE CALL FROM   JOE SANDERS THAT AFTERNOON CONFIRMED THAT THEY WOULD LOOK AT THE PACKAGE SOMETIME   ON MONDAY 8-21-06. AWAITING WORD FROM FAA REGARDING THE PACKAGE DISPOSITION AT   THIS TIME.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING AS A RESULT OF ONE   OF THE INNER PLASTIC BOTTLES FAILING. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AS IT WAS SUSPECTED   THAT THE PAINT PRODUCT MIGHT BE A DANGEROUS GOOD PRODUCT, EVEN THOUGH THE SHIPPERS   STATEMENT SAID IT WAS NON HAZARDOUS ON THE COMMERCIAL INVOICE. AFTER NUMEROUS   ATTEMPTS TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER FAILED, I NOTIFIED THE SJU/FAA BY VOICE MAIL ON   WEDNESDAY 8-23-06 AT 15:25 OF THE PACKAGE THAT IS BEING HELD FOR THEIR   INVESTIGATION. I SPOKE TO FAA AGENT JUAN BULTED ON THURSDAY 8-24-06 AT 11:30 TO   FOLLOW-UP THAT THE INVESTIGATION HAD BEGUN BY HIS OFFICE.

THE SHIPMENT ARRIVED WITH A COMPLAINT OF AN ODOR FROM THE FIRST OFFICER. WHEN THE DG MANAGER AND SPECIALIST OPENED HAZ CAN THE ODOR WAS MORE PRONOUNCED, AND IT QUICKLY DISSIPATED. ADDITIONAL INFORMATION F/O STATED THAT HE REPORTED THE ODOR TO RAMP PERSONNEL UPON ARRIVAL. F/O STATED HE CALLED THE DO BETWEEN 3:30-4:30 AM TO REPORT INCIDENT AND ILLNESS. D. F/O STATED THAT WHEN HE WAS INSPECTING THE HAZ CAN, HE SMELLED AN ODOR THAT COULD HAVE BEEN THE JET FUEL. 2. 2:05 PM - JUMPSEATER DAN DILL (96533) REPORTED THAT HE SMELLED THE ODOR IN OAK, BUT WHEN THE DOOR WAS CLOSED IT SEEMED TO DISSIPATE. A. AFTER LANDING AT LAX, THE AIRCRAFT HAD A LONG TAXI TIME TO THE RAMP AND THE ODOR CAME BACK. BY THE TIME THE AIRCRAFT STOPPED AT THE GATE, THE JUMPSEATER FELT NAUSEOUS. HE DID NOT SEEK TREATMENT AND FELT FINE.

DURING THE SORT OPERATION IN ANCHORAGE, THIS SHIPMENT WAS CHECKED BY U.S. CUSTOMS AND FOUND TO CONTAIN THREE DIFFERENT TYPES OF SMALL ARMS AMMUNITION, PLUS CAMPING STOVE FUELS AND A BOX OF STRIKE ANYWHERE MATCHES. SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED OR DOCUMENTED TO CONTAIN DANGEROUS GOODS. SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. LOCAL FAA OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: Two boxes filled with nail polish and other consumer commodity items shipped in non-UN specification packaging, without cushioning. Over 100 bottles of nail polish (Salley Hansen Diamond Strength) was in each box. One box contained 47 bottles of aerosol (Airbrush Sun) and over 100 bottles of nail polish. The aerosol is UN 1950, Aerosols, Class 2.1 Dangerous Goods. Only one nail polish bottle leaked. The other package was opened to investigate contents. Obtained MSDS’s and pictures. Holding at station per DG Admin (T J Leech).

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: This shipment appears to have been damaged by other freight. The shipment contained paint related materials. The MSDS for the material indicates it has a Flash point which would make it a Class 3, flammable liquid. The shipment was not marked, labeled or documented to contain dangerous goods. The FAA was notified and the shipment is being held pending FAA investigation.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: THE TRAINMASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN WILLARD, OH REPORTED THAT A CAR INSPECTOR HAD DETECTED A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR IN TRACKS E07 AND E08.  THE TRAINMASTER INSPECTED THE TRACK AND ADVISED THAT THE ODOR WAS STRONGEST AROUND GATX 300869, LOAD AMMONIA SOLUTIONS.  THE AREA AROUND THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, EAGLE CONSTRUCTION, TO REPAIR THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE.  THE SHIPPER, TERRA INTERNATIONAL,WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC (REPORT #08082006092).  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT PRODUCT VAPORS WERE BEING RELEASED THROUGH THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  THE CONTRACTOR RELIEVED THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR AND INSTALLED A REPLACEMENT VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  THE VAPOR RELEASE WAS STOPPED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE DEFECTS FOUND AND THE ACTIONS TAKEN TO STOP THE RELEASE.  TERRA TO HAVE A RAIL CAR REPAIR COMPANY RESPOND TO CHECK THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE BEFORE THE CAR WILL BE RELEASED.    CAUSE CODE:456    NARRI:5(5+3+0)X(2+0)=80

column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE FERTILIZERS WITH NOT MORE THAN 0.2 PERCENT CARBON
column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap; Misaligned Material, Component, or Device
column168: 13 AUGUST 2006, JACKSON CITY, KENTUCKY, 1530 HOURS, JACKSON CITY POLICE WHILE ON PATROL NOTICED A WHITE POWDER SUBSTANCE UNDER A RAILCAR IN THE CSXT JACKSON YARD.  THE POLICE DISPATCHERS OFFICE CONTACTED CSX-PSCC REQUESTING INFORMATION ON RAILCARS UNPX 120069 & AEX 5816 WERE LOADS OF UN1942, AMMONIUM NITRATE.  THE TERP-TRANSPORTATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN WAS ACTIVATED AND THE POLICE DISPATCHER AND THE HAZMAT CALL DUTY OFFICER DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT RELEASED WAS AMMONIUM NITRATE.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR PECCO ENVIRONMENT SERVICES, NICHOLASVILLE, KY RESPONDED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED AMMONIUM NITRATE.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 1622 HOURS REPORT #08132006010. CSXT CAR DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED TO INVESTIGATE AND CLOSE THE HOPPER GATE.  INSPECTION DETERMINED AEX 5816 LEAKED PRODUCT.  A ROCK WAS FOUND WEDGET IN THE LEFT SIDE OF HOPPER SLIDE DOOR #2.  THE ROCK WAS REMOVED, THE DOOR CLOSED AND WOODEN WEDGES APPLIED.  PECCO ENV. CLEANED UP AND DRUMMED THREE 55 GALLON DRUMS OF SPILLED PRODUCT FOR DISPOSAL.  UNPX 120069 WAS SEALED AND HAD NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  CODE=662  NARRI: 5(5+1+0)X(5+0)=150

column168: DRIVER WHILE ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER GASOLINE TO AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK, FAILED TO CONNECT HIS DELIVERY HOSE TO THE GROUND CONNECTION PRIOR TO STARTING DELIVERY.  THIS RESULTED IN A 60-75 GALLON GASOLINE RELEASE.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED BY THE DRIVER ON STATION PROPERTY FOR THE MOST PART ALTHOUGH SOME DID RUN DOWN THE ROADWAY FOR ABOUT 100 FEET AND ENTERED A STORM DRAIN.  THE NEWARK, DE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE DRIVER'S CALL.  MR. BILL FOUNTAIN FROM THE DELAWARE DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL (DNREC) ARRIVED SHORTLY AFTERWARDS.  GUARDIAN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC, BEAR, DE. WAS CONTACTED TO DO THE CLEANUP.  ROUTE 72 WAS SHUT DOWN FOR MORE THAN AN HOUR BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  COAST GUARD NATIONAL RESPONSE WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THE RELEASE AND ROAD CLOSURE.  REPORT #807041 APPLIES.  GUARDIAN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ARRIVED ABOUT 0100 AND COMPLETED THE CLEANUP AT APPROXIMATELY 0400.  BOOMS WERE LEFT IN THE STORM DRAIN TO ABSORB ANY RESIDUE PRODUCT AND WILL BE REMOVED AFTER THE NEXT RAIN EVENT.  DNREC REP, (MR. JAMIE BETHARD) INSPECTED CLEANUP AND RELEASED CLEANUP CONTRACTOR.
column169: DRIVER WAS RETRAINED ON PROPER DELIVERY PROCEDURES.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER DELIVERING GAS TO UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK.  DRIVER HAD TWO DELIVERY HOSES LAYING ON THE GROUND.  WHEN HE CONNECTED THE FIRST HOSE AND STARTED TO DROP, HE NOTICED A LEAK AT THE DISCHARGE VALVE.  HE STOPPED THE PRODUCT FLOW, DRAINED THE HOSE, RECONNECTED AND STARTED DELIVERING AGAIN.  THE LEAK CONTINUED SO HE DISCONNECTED AND RECONNECTED IN THIS MANNER SEVERAL MORE TIMES.  THE LAST TIME HE LAID THE HOSE ON THE GROUND AND REPLACED THE GASKET ON THE DISCHARGE VALVE.  WHEN HE WAS READY TO RECONNECT THE HOSE, HE PICKED UP THE WRONG HOSE AND CONNECTED IT TO THE COMPARTMENT.  WITHOUT LOOKING TO SEE IF IT WAS THE RIGHT HOSE AND WAS CONNECTED TO THE GROUND FITTING, HE PULLED THE DISCHARGE VALVE AND CAUSED A 20 GALLON RELEASE.    RELEASE CLEANED UP BY IN-HOUSE RESPONSE TEAM    DELAWARE DNREC (CHRISTOPHER L BERLIN) ON SITE
column169: DRIVER RETRAINED ON PROPER DELIVERY PROCEDURES.

column168: Mitch Bullock, Car Foreman, reported Tank car UTLX 12188 was releasing gas and an unknown amount of product from the top of the tank car in the Green River Rail yard in Green River, WY. Mr. Bullock advised no injuries were reported. Mark Reimers, Regional Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and stated he would contact ft M. Cat, Contractor. Mr. Reimers requested Kim Keeling, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, be notified. Necessary state notification was made. At 06:47 PM, Kim Keeling, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, advised Leon Hendrickson, Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, and R. M. Cat, Contractor, were responding. At 07:24 PM, Hendrickson advised he was en route with an estimated time of arrival of three hours. At 08:55 PM, Kim Keeling, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, advised approximately three gallons of product was released because the bolts on the liquid line eduction flange were loose causing the 9asket to become displaced. Mr. Keeling further advised Bob Leebmitz, Simplot, secured the tank car and neutralized spilled product with soda ash. R. M. Cat, Contractor, was instructed to disregard. Hendrickson was updated and advised he would continue response to ensure remediation was completed. Mr. Hendrickson advised that the areas where the tank car was were clean and free of product.

JIM, CORRIDOR MANAGER, REPORTED HAZMAT TANKCAR ACFX 95722 VENTING AND POSSIBLY RELEASING PRODUCT ON WESTBOUND TRAIN MNPST 10, LEAD LOCOMOTIVE UP 8489, AT MILE POST 380.0 OF THE SIDNEY SUBDIVISION IN CHAPPELL, NE. JIM FURTHER STATED THE TRAIN CREW WAS CLEARED FROM THE AREA AND THE MAIN LINE SHUT DOWN DUE TO REPORTED VAPOR BLOWING ACROSS THE TRACK WITH NO REPORTED INJURIES OR EXPOSURES. KIM KEELING, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. LORI, CHAPPELL FIRE DEPARTMENT, WAS NOTIFIED AND STATED FIRE RESPONDERS WOULD BE DISPATCHED. ALL REQUIRED STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE COMPLETED. AT 03:19 PM, JIM, CORRIDOR MANAGER, ADVISED THE CHAPPELL FIRE DEPARTMENT FIRE MARSHALL ORDERED THE TRAIN TO MOVE AT LEAST THREE MILES CLEAR OF THE TOWN OF CHAPPELL, NE. TO MILE POST 383.5. AT 05:38 PM, MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, ADVISED HE WAS IN CONTACT WITH KEELING, WHO STATED AT 05:26 PM, THE TANKCAR LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE TANK CAR WAS IN THE PROCESS OF BEING MOVED TO A SIDING TO CLEAR THE MAIN LINE TRACK. MR. KEELING ADVISED THE CAUSE OF THE TEAK WAS THE MAIN LIQUID VALVE ASSEMBLY ON THE EDUCTION LINE WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT. MR. KEELING ADVISED HE ROTATED THE ASSEMBLY 180 DEGREES WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. AT 07:07 PM, KEELING ADVISED HE HAD RECHECKED THE TANKCAR AND IT WAS SECURED WITH NO OTHER RELEASES LOCATED. THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO RESUME TRANSPORTATION.

column168: Katrina, Manager Intermodal Operations, reported a strong odor emitted from Container BLKU 252672, located at the ramp inside the Englewood Yard in Houston, TX. Katrina stated there was no visible release. Geoffrey Reeder, Environmental Site Remediation, was notified and responded. Upon arrival at the scene, Reeder inspected the tank container. There was no sign of a liquid release. The wing bolts on the man way cover were tightened. The valve on the air line was open and the plug loose. The valve was closed and the plug tightened. The placards on the container were faded. The product name was also faded. The emergency response telephone number on the shipping paper was incorrect. Reeder requested all be corrected prior to the container leaving the yard.

column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE, WITH NOT MORE THAN 0.2%  OF COMBUSTIBLE MATERIALS, INCLUDING ANY ORGANIC SUBSTANCE CALCULATED AS CARBON TO THE EXCLUSION OF ANY OTHER ADDED SUBSTANCE
column168: CSX Transportation, Inc was advised by Agricultural Services of Montgomery, AL, that they had discovered covered hopper, WC 82051, loaded with Ammonium Nitrate, to be leaking product. CSXT delivered the car to Agricultural Services during the night of 08/14/06. The general car foreman inspected the car at the customer’s facility and reported that the B-end slope sheet on the end compartment was corroded through. CSXT hazardous material department notified the shipper, Terra Nitrogen Corp. of the incident via CHEMTREC (report # 08152006043). CSXT responded an emergency response contractor to plug the hole in the car’s slope sheet and to initiate the cleanup of the released product. Agricultural Services advised that they would unload the car and recover the product that was released on their property. The contractor recovered approximately 3 tons of product that had been released from the car in CSXT’s yard and in the track from the yard to the consignee’s facility. Agricultural Services agreed to accept and reclaim all of the recovered product. After the car was unloaded, Agricultural Services cleaned the car and removed the placards so that the empty car could be shopped for repairs.   CAUSE CODE = 662   NARRI: 2(5+1+0) x (4+0) = 48

column168: ON 08/20/2006 AT 1600 THE PSCC CALLED AVON IN, TRAINMASTER LANCE ROBINSON.  HE REPORTED THAT, LOADED TANK CAR CGTX 30421 HAD A SMALL BUT STEADY STREAM OF LIQUID COMING FROM UNDER THE DOME ON THE TOP OF THE RAIL CAR.  THE CAR WAS SWITCHED OUT OF THE TRACK AND ISOLATED IN THE TRAIN YARD.  ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR FROM SUMMIT, INDIANAPOLIS, WAS CALLED TO SEAL THE TANK CAR.  ONCE ON THE PROPERTY THEY OPENED THE DOME AND FOUND PRODUCT LEAKING FROM UNDER THE LIQUID LINE.  THE VAPOR LINE WAS OPENED TO BLEED OFF THE PRESSURE AND THE LIQUID LINE CAP WAS REMOVED.  THE PIPE AND VALVE WERE CLEANED AND TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED TO BOTH.  THE VALVE WAS REAPPLIED TOOL TIGHT AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS RESEALED AND SENT TO DESTINATION FOR UNLOADING.  THE SHIPPER, IMPERIAL OIL OF SARNIA ON, WAS CONTACTED TO HAVE THE CAR SHOPPED AND SENT TO A QUALIFIED SHOP TO BE RESTESTED AND QUALIFIED.    NARRI: 2(5+1+0)X(2+0)=24  CAUSE CODE: 282

GENERAL CAR FOREMEN CARLO ADVISED THAT CAR HAD LEAKED FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AND PRODUCT SPILLED DOWN THE SIDES.  YARD CREW PLACED BUCKET UNDER THE CAR TO COLLECT SPILLED PRODUCT.  SPSI ARRIVED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE FLANGE BOLTS OF THE LIQUID LINE. THE FLANGE BOLTS FOR THE VAPOR VALVE WERE ALSO FOUND NOT TO BE TOOL TIGHT.  THE SERVICE PLATE FLANGE BOLTS AND VAPOR VALVE WERE ALL MADE TOOL TIGHT.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO VERIFY THAT THERE WAS NO MORE PRODUCT RELEASE.  SPSI CLEANED AND DECONNED THE CAR AND IT WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.    NARRI: 5(5+5+0)(2+0)=100  CAUSE CODE=62  CHEMTREC REPORT#08232006021

An inbound BNSF intermodal train arriving at the BNSF intermodal facility was observed with an unknown semi-liquid white substance on two entrained intermodal containers atop rail flatcars. These containers were deramped and taken to the containment area for further inspection. One container’s lading was inspected and the lading appeared intact. BNSF contract responders cleaned the outside of this intermodal container. The other container, TRLU 480314, was inspected and sustained a load shift of the lading inside container. The load shift was caused by poor stowage, improper and insufficient blocking and bracing. Several 5-gallon poly pails of cleaning detergents destined for vessel movement to Hawaii were damaged and leaking. The poly pails were stacked on pallets and only secured by plastic stretch-wrap. The pails on the bottom pallet were stacked 3- high and the top pallet pails were stacked 2-high. The top pails toppled over into voids inside the container. The bottom pails loosened on the pallet and leaned into other pails on pallets behind them. In total, 32 poly pails had released product and many others were dented, but did not leak. Eleven 5-gallon poly pails of industrial detergent containing Potassium & Sodium Hydroxide solutions were dented, cracked and leaked. Salvageable pails were overpacked and returned to the neutralized, cleaned and reworked container, properly blocked and braced. The cleaning materials and unsalvageable pails were earmarked for appropriate disposal by the response contractor. American Pacific Forwarding subsequently transferred the lading inside TRLU 480314 into another container prior to vessel loading. Also see BNSF DOT 5800.1 report 06-0817-01 B.

column168: Richard WuLff, Alton and Southern Mechanical Superintendent, reported a strong odor emitted from Tankcar HOKX 7948 located in the Alton and Southern Railyard at 1000 South 22nd Street in East Saint Louis, IL. Mr. Wulff advised there were no injuries, evacuations, exposures, nor fires. John Miller, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, was notified and responded. All state and federal notifications were completed. At 11:55 AM, Miller advised that the liquid valve was partially open and the cap was corroded to the point that it could not be tightened causing a vapor release of product. The shipper was contacted and delivered a new cap. The car was properly sealed and returned to transportation.

Rick Cook, Signal Maintainer, reported Tankcar GATX 300548 had released a liquid from the pressure valve at the top of the tankcar. Robert Bavier, Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and responded. At 06:10 PM, Bavier advised the release was due to improper loading practices and was not caused by any damage to the tank car. The car was set out. United Pumping Services responded to clean the tank car of spilled material. On 08/18/2006, at 12:47 AM, Bavier advised the tankcar was decontaminated and released to transportation.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Liquid Valve
column168: At 1 654hrs on 8-25-06, Frank Lerch, Manager Chemical Transportation Safety was contacted by the RMCC, and advised that Selandras Villanueva, Manager of Yard Operations, reported tank car UTLX 23502 to be leaking from the top of the car. Car was located on the south end of track 214 Strang Yard. Upon being notified, Mgr. Lerch requested RMCO make shipper notification via Chem-Trec.     On arrival, Mgr. Lerch noted product leaking from the liquid valve. Inspection of the 3 liquid ball valve, revealed the plug to be in position, loose one turn, and the valve to be slightly open approximately 1/8th rotation. Upon closing of the valve, and tightening of the plug, the leak was stopped and the car secured from further release. Further inspection of the car revealed that one of four flange bolts which attach the air valve assembly to be loose, and the air valve plug to be in position, loose one turn. It should be noted that no product was leaking from the air valve assembly.     There were no reported injuries, drains, or waterways impacted resulting from this release. No further remediation was necessary, as product evaporated upon contact with the atmosphere. After correcting all noted exceptions, the car was released to continue onto destination without further incident.

column168: Tom Richardson, North Platte Express Agent, reported Tankcar ADMX 30622 was releasing an unknown amount of product on Track 222 in Yard One in North Platte, NE, with no injuries or waterways affected. The North Platte Express Agent advised the liquid product was releasing from the top of the tankcar, possibly due to being over-filled. Mark Ross, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, was notified and stated he would investigate the incident. State agencies were notified. At 03:11 PM, Kim Keeling, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, advised Hazmat Response would be dispatched for remediation. At 04:11 PM, Keeling advised Hazmat Response had tightened the packing gland nut of the liquid valve, which stopped the release. Mr. Keeling stated no digging would be required, as the product evaporated on contact with the atmosphere.

column168: A nearby plant reported Tankcar ACFX 75632 appeared to be releasing vapor near County Road 2427e in Hull, TX. Timothy O’Brien, Regional Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and responded. The train was relocated to Mile Post 433to be inspected. Mr.O’Brien, inspected the train and was able to confirm there was a release of vapor from the suspect tank car. Mr. O’Brien found three bolts on the flange for the relief valve were loose which resulted in the vapor only release. The flange bolts were tightened, the release stopped and the car released for transportation.
